===Etymology 2===
Possibly from {{m|en|aye}}.

The pirate-imitation form was derived from the West Country dialect after its use by West Country-born actor {{w|Robert Newton}} in the films ''{{w|Treasure Island (1950 film)|Treasure Island}}'' (1950) and ''{{w|Blackbeard the Pirate}}'' (1952), and the former's spin-off media, in which he played, respectively, fictional pirate Long John Silver and historical pirate Edward "Blackbeard" Teach (who was also a West Country native).<ref>{{cite-book|title=Cornwall's Strangest Tales|first=Peter|last=Grego|publisher=Pavilion Books|year=2013|isbn=9781909396432|chapter="Aharrr, Jim Lad!"}}</ref><ref>{{cite-book|title=Handsome Heroes and Vile Villains: Masculinity in Disney's Feature Films|first=Amy M.|last=Davis|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780861969074|page=193}}</ref><ref>{{cite-book|title=Exmouth to Plymouth: Britain's Heritage Coast|first=Gary|last=Holpin|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|year=2014|isbn=9781445621579}}</ref>

